04539nam a22005535i 9780226088747DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013016604  a9780226088747  a(DE-B1597)550295  a(OCoLC)878405941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH15b.T47 2014 4aQH15b.T47 2014eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a508223  aTB 3281qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/143750:137451 aTerrall, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatching Nature in the Act :bRéaumur and the Practice of Natural History in the Eighteenth Century /cMary Terrall. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b46 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 The Terrain of Natural History -- t2 “Catching Nature in the Act” -- t3 Seeing Again and Again -- t4 Recruiting Observers and Training “Philosophical Eyes” -- t5 Natural Prodigies -- t6 A Spectacle Pleasing to the Mind -- t7 Chickens, Eggs, and the Perennial Question of the Generation of Animals -- tEpilogue. -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNatural history in the eighteenth century was many things to many people—diversion, obsession, medically or economically useful knowledge, spectacle, evidence for God’s providence and wisdom, or even the foundation of all natural knowledge. Because natural history was pursued by such a variety of people around the globe, with practitioners sharing neither methods nor training, it has been characterized as a science of straightforward description, devoted to amassing observations as the raw material for classification and thus fundamentally distinct from experimental physical science. In Catching Nature in the Act, Mary Terrall revises this picture, revealing how eighteenth-century natural historians incorporated various experimental techniques and strategies into their practice. At the center of Terrall’s study is René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur (1683–1757)—the definitive authority on natural history in the middle decades of the eighteenth century—and his many correspondents, assistants, and collaborators. Through a close examination of Réaumur’s publications, papers, and letters, Terrall reconstructs the working relationships among these naturalists and shows how observing, collecting, and experimenting fit into their daily lives. Essential reading for historians of science and early modern Europe, Catching Nature in the Act defines and excavates a dynamic field of francophone natural history that has been inadequately mined and understood to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNatural historyxHistoryx18th century. 0aNatural historyxHistoryy18th century. 0aNaturalistsxHistoryx18th century. 0aNaturalistsxHistoryy18th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anatural world, outdoors, reaumur, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, biographical, 18th century, 1700s, knowledge, faith, belief, environment, environmental, physical, science, scientific, global, international, observation, classification, relationships, letters, correspondence, documents, archival, experimental, collaborative, daily life, francophone, reproduction, regeneration, asexual.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226088747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226088747/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles